{"name": "pytket-qirpass", "metadata": {"name": "pytket-qirpass", "version": "0.8.0", "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License"], "home_page": null, "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["llvmlite", "pytket"], "summary": "Module for optimizing QIR using pytket.", "upload_time": 1732534040}, "documentation": ["# pytket-qirpass\n\nThis module provides a method to optimize QIR using pytket.\n\n## Installation\n\nPython 3.10, 3.11, 3.12 or 3.13 is required.\n\nTo install from PyPI:\n\n```shell\npip install pytket-qirpass\n```\n\n## Usage\n\nThis module provides a single function, `apply_qirpass`, which takes as input\n\n- some QIR bitcode\n- a pytket compilation pass\n- a target gateset\n\nand outputs some new QIR bitcode, where the pass has been applied to the basic\nblocks in the input program, followed by a rebase to the target gateset.\n\nFor example:\n\n```python\nfrom pytket_qirpass import apply_qirpass\nfrom pytket.circuit import OpType\nfrom pytket.passes import FullPeepholeOptimise\n\nqir_out = apply_qirpass(\n    qir_bitcode=qir_in,\n    comp_pass=FullPeepholeOptimise(allow_swaps=False),\n    target_1q_gates={OpType.Rx, OpType.Rz},\n    target_2q_gates={OpType.ZZPhase},\n)\n```\n\nBoth the input and the output are Python `bytes` objects.\n\nProvided the pass preserves the circuit semantics, `apply_qirpass` preserves\nthe QIR semantics.\n"], "modules": [{"name": "pytket_qirpass", "documentation": ["Module for optimizing QIR using pytket."], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "pytket_qirpass.__version__", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "pytket_qirpass.apply_qirpass", "xref": {"fqname": "pytket_qirpass.apply_qirpass.apply_qirpass", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "pytket_qirpass.apply_qirpass", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "pytket_qirpass.apply_qirpass.encode_double", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "a", "type": {"name": "float", "xref": {"fqna